Docker Networking:
------------------

Docker networking lets containers communicate with:
----------------------------------------------------
Each other
The host machine
The outside internet
  
Why do we need Docker networks?
---------------------------------
Imagine you have:

+----------------------+
| Grafana Container    |
+----------------------+
           |
           | needs data from
           |
+----------------------+
| InfluxDB Container   |
+----------------------+

If both containers are on the same Docker network, Grafana can connect to InfluxDB using the container name.


Docker Network Types:
======================
  
Network                          	Purpose
======================================================
bridge	                          Default network for containers
host	                            Container shares the host's network
none	                            No network access
custom bridge                   	ser-created network (most common in real projects)


Example
===============
Create a network:
==========================
docker network create solar-network
=================================================
Run InfluxDB:
=====================
docker run -d \
  --name influxdb \
  --network solar-network \
  influxdb:2

Run Grafana:
====================
docker run -d \
  --name grafana \
  --network solar-network \
  -p 3000:3000 \
  grafana/grafana

Now Grafana can reach InfluxDB using:
============================================
http://influxdb:8086
---------------------------------------------------------------
because both containers are on the same network.
--------------------------------------------------------


Now from the Grafana container:
============================
ping influxdb
=================
or

curl http://influxdb:8086
================================
will reach the InfluxDB container.
=================================

